{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659769"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:14:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:14:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20888"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20888"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0,0.08,0.04,0.77]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13763"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96735"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13763"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20888"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79354"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11727"},{"type":"tags","id":"12714"},{"type":"tags","id":"12715"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33160"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33163"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96735"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes transcription errors in laboratory medicine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Errors occurring during centrifugation of samples","Improper sample collection techniques","Errors in result interpretation by clinicians","Contamination of specimens during aliquoting","Incorrect entry of patient or test information into systems"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncorrect entry of patient or test information into systems\u003C/strong\u003E accurately describes transcription errors in laboratory medicine. These errors typically occur when laboratory staff manually enter patient demographics, test requests, or results into laboratory information systems. Transcription errors are particularly common in facilities that do not use electronic order-entry systems, where handwritten requisition forms must be manually entered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErrors occurring during centrifugation of samples\u003C/strong\u003E - These are processing errors related to sample preparation, not transcription errors. Examples include insufficient centrifugation time or incorrect speed.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContamination of specimens during aliquoting\u003C/strong\u003E - This represents a sample integrity issue during the physical handling of specimens, not a transcription error.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImproper sample collection techniques\u003C/strong\u003E - These are pre-analytical errors that occur before the sample reaches the laboratory, such as incorrect tube filling or improper venipuncture technique.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErrors in result interpretation by clinicians\u003C/strong\u003E - These are post-analytical errors that occur after testing is complete and results are reported.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAutomation of laboratory processes, including the use of pre-analytical workstations and electronic order-entry systems, significantly reduces the risk of transcription errors by minimizing manual data entry. Barcode systems and interfaced analyzers further reduce the opportunity for human error in the laboratory workflow.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Transcription errors occur when patient or test information is incorrectly entered into laboratory information systems, particularly in facilities without electronic order-entry systems.","Automation of sample preparation steps using pre-analytical workstations reduces the risk of human errors in laboratory processing.","Laboratory sample processing involves multiple steps including registration, centrifugation, decapping, aliquoting, and sorting, each with potential for error."],"references":["Mrazek C, Lippi G, Keppel MH, Felder TK, Oberkofler H, Haschke-Becher E, Cadamuro J. Errors within the total laboratory testing process, from test selection to medical decision-making - A review of causes, consequences, surveillance and solutions. Biochem Med (Zagreb). 2020 Jun 15;30(2):020502. doi: 10.11613/BM.2020.020502. PMID: 32550813; PMCID: PMC7271754.  Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7271754/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79354"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20888"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79354"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T17:33:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T17:34:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13763"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96735"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11260","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11260"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2696\ufe0f","name":"Professionalism","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-01-14T04:23:20